because people were like,

12:29.282 --> 12:31.384
"Oh, my gosh,
this looks like satin,

12:31.484 --> 12:32.518
but I see these curvy women
in it."

12:32.619 --> 12:34.120
It's insane.
Which, typically...

12:34.220 --> 12:35.622
Yeah, you're right.
...curvy women
cannot wear satin.

12:35.722 --> 12:37.223
Help me understand.

12:37.323 --> 12:39.959
I mean, Emma and Lori
right away went,

12:40.059 --> 12:41.227
"Ooh, this is great."

12:41.327 --> 12:43.963
And I'm sitting here going,
"Why is this great?"

12:44.063 --> 12:46.366
The key is really
the stretch in the fabric.

12:46.466 --> 12:47.567
It's so stretchy.
It can go in bags.

12:47.667 --> 12:50.036
So it drapes your curves.
It drapes your curves.

12:50.136 --> 12:52.639
But this also really helps you
with returns, right?

12:52.739 --> 12:54.007
Yes, absolutely.

12:54.107 --> 12:55.074
Because if you've got
a fabric like this,

12:55.174 --> 12:56.743
with this crazy amount
of stretch in it,

12:56.843 --> 12:57.977
you're not getting
the same returns... Exactly.

12:58.077 --> 12:59.112
...as with
a rigid fabric.

12:59.212 --> 13:00.246
Tell us about sales.

13:00.346 --> 13:02.582
We have lifetime sales
of $2 million.

13:02.682 --> 13:03.650
$2 million?

13:03.750 --> 13:05.418
Wow.
Yes, $2 million.

13:05.518 --> 13:07.287
Wow!
But I also want to talk to you
about our growth.

13:07.387 --> 13:10.256
So year to date,
we're at $850,000.

13:10.356 --> 13:11.491
In year one,
we were at $30,000.

13:11.591 --> 13:13.593
Which year was that, too?
What year was that?

13:13.693 --> 13:16.929
2019. In year two,
we were at $200,000.

13:17.030 --> 13:20.633
So it was a nice jump, but
we were almost five times that

13:20.733 --> 13:23.503
in year three,
with $950,000.

13:23.603 --> 13:25.471
Now, we were a little shy
of our goal of $1 million,

13:25.571 --> 13:28.007
but we're projected to be
there this year, at $1.2
million.

13:28.107 --> 13:29.242
- Wow.
- Wow!

13:29.342 --> 13:30.743
That's major, guys.

13:30.843 --> 13:32.145
Are you profitable?

13:32.245 --> 13:34.714
Last year,
we made $20,000.

13:34.814 --> 13:36.115
Are you paying yourselves
a salary?

13:36.215 --> 13:37.250
$60,000.

13:37.350 --> 13:38.785
Each or total?
Each.

13:38.885 --> 13:39.952
Alright, that's fine.

13:40.053 --> 13:42.021
How much are you guys
spending on advertising?

13:42.121 --> 13:46.326
So, we spend about 30%
of our revenue on advertising,

13:46.426 --> 13:49.095
and that's super important,
because each customer

13:49.195 --> 13:52.065
we bring in
is not just one customer.

13:52.165 --> 13:55.468
Right, of course. Right.
If we can bring in a bride,
that's eight bridesmaids.

13:55.568 --> 13:57.537
I know this business
incredibly well.

13:57.637 --> 13:59.672
I make inclusive sizing
at both SKIMS and Good American.

13:59.772 --> 14:00.907
Yes.

14:01.007 --> 14:02.709
And it makes the margin
profile really tricky.

14:02.809 --> 14:05.611
So talk to me about margins
on both of the ranges, please.

14:05.712 --> 14:08.581
So, we're at 70%
for both of the ranges.

14:08.681 --> 14:10.216
For your
direct-to-consumer sales?

14:10.316 --> 14:12.352
Yeah.
We only sell direct.

14:12.452 --> 14:14.721
Can you please tell me
both of your backgrounds?

14:14.821 --> 14:17.357
I was in marketing for
a little over a decade

14:17.457 --> 14:18.725
before coming
full-time.

14:18.825 --> 14:20.460
I worked for
huge CPG brands

14:20.560 --> 14:22.862
like Neutrogena,
The Laughing Cow. Wow.

14:22.962 --> 14:25.465
I was actually doing some of,
like, the first Facebook ads,

14:25.565 --> 14:26.799
back in 2009,

14:26.899 --> 14:29.068
so that's why I'm kind of like
the digital person.

14:29.168 --> 14:30.903
Gotcha. Thank you.
And you?

14:31.003 --> 14:34.006
Yes. I played football
most of my life.

14:34.107 --> 14:36.376
Afterwards, I became
a child psychiatric specialist

14:36.476 --> 14:38.511
at a children's hospital,
and then I moved

14:38.611 --> 14:40.680
into law enforcement
and became a detective.

14:40.780 --> 14:42.615
Wow. Are you still a
detective, or do you do this
full-time?

14:42.715 --> 14:44.917
No. Actually,
I left the police force

14:45.051 --> 14:46.719
to completely
follow this dream.

14:46.819 --> 14:48.121
So, guys,
what's the vision?

14:48.221 --> 14:49.522
What do you want to do
with this brand?

14:49.622 --> 14:52.792
The biggest thing for us
is showcasing diversity

14:52.892 --> 14:56.195
in a space that never saw
brides and couples

14:56.295 --> 15:00.032
or even bridesmaids of color
in media campaigns.

15:00.133 --> 15:02.602
So it's so important to us
to have that component.

15:02.702 --> 15:05.705
And making sure that we are
celebrating all body types.

15:05.805 --> 15:07.673
And how big do you want
to take the business?

15:07.774 --> 15:09.742
Well, Charles has
a huge vision.

15:09.842 --> 15:11.310
We want to be
a $500 million company.

15:11.411 --> 15:12.512
Whoa.

15:12.612 --> 15:15.047
The real question I have is,
what do you need?

15:15.148 --> 15:17.817
For you to get to $500
million, what are those first steps

15:17.917 --> 15:19.519
you need to take,
and where do you need help?

15:19.619 --> 15:21.754
So we want to get more
team members

15:21.854 --> 15:23.689
to create
supply-chain efficiency,

15:23.790 --> 15:25.858
because we want to be able
to get the customers

15:25.958 --> 15:27.827
what they need, when they
need, as fast as we can.

15:27.927 --> 15:29.462
How many people do you
have working for you?

15:29.562 --> 15:31.330
It's just the two of us
full time.

15:31.431 --> 15:33.933
Charles has one contractor
that he works with seasonally.

15:34.033 --> 15:35.268
So when you guys
get orders,

15:35.368 --> 15:36.335
you just grind it out
in the warehouse that you
have?

15:36.436 --> 15:37.136
Yes.
Yes.

15:37.236 --> 15:38.337
- Wow.
- That's amazing.

15:38.438 --> 15:40.440
Okay, so who's actually
making the dresses?

15:40.540 --> 15:43.543
So, we have a number
of manufacturers overseas.

15:43.643 --> 15:46.078
What's your lead time
on-- on a dress or dresses?

15:46.179 --> 15:49.982
It takes about two to
three weeks to actually
produce the dresses.

15:50.082 --> 15:51.984
But then, shipping,
I'm sure you all know,

15:52.084 --> 15:53.186
has been kind of
a nightmare.

15:53.286 --> 15:54.420
Right. So you're having--
Pain in the ass right now.

15:54.520 --> 15:56.255
So because we've been
selling out so quickly,

15:56.355 --> 15:59.125
we've had to incur additional
cost to do air shipping.

15:59.225 --> 16:00.993
Well, first of all,
super impressive.

16:01.093 --> 16:04.831
I love the business,
but I-I can't add value

16:04.931 --> 16:06.866
in the bridal dress business.

16:06.966 --> 16:08.768
It's just not
my forte.

16:08.868 --> 16:11.103
Thank you for coming,
but I'm out.

16:11.204 --> 16:12.338
Thank you.
Thank you.

16:12.438 --> 16:15.341
Guys, I'm-- I'm very
impressed. I'm in this space.

16:15.441 --> 16:18.010
I don't know if you know your
customer acquisition cost yet.

16:18.110 --> 16:19.946
It's one of the highest
in the fashion business,

16:20.046 --> 16:21.147
is capturing the bride

16:21.247 --> 16:22.849
when she's making
her purchase decision.

16:22.949 --> 16:24.917
Yes.
I wish you the best,
but it's-- it's not for me.

16:25.051 --> 16:25.985
I'm out.

16:26.085 --> 16:26.986
Thank you.
Thank you.

16:27.086 --> 16:28.988
Guys, listen,
I love the fact

16:29.088 --> 16:31.357
that you've managed
to stay out of the trap

16:31.457 --> 16:33.726
of the kind of
traditional wedding business,

16:33.826 --> 16:36.829
because it's my belief that
any brand that's going to scale

16:36.929 --> 16:38.297
and do really well now

16:38.397 --> 16:40.299
has to be rooted
in some kind of community.

16:40.399 --> 16:43.836
It's the only way that we can
keep advertising cost down

16:43.936 --> 16:45.338
and keep that
word of mouth going

16:45.438 --> 16:47.039
and keep the
customers excited.

16:47.139 --> 16:48.741
There's so much promise
in this business,

16:48.841 --> 16:52.011
so I definitely would love
to give you guys an offer.

